Hi Roy,


Have you considered where you wish to retire to? As expats who have spent much of their working lives abroad, this may be a difficult decision. Stay abroad; or return to the place of childhood.  

There are many things to consider. Here are some key points to help you on your journey;


1. The 'Pension Gap' - People need to plan on supporting themselves in retirement for 30+ years. Do you have sufficient financial provision to support retirement in your chosen destination?


2. The State of your Health – With age the need to access quality medical services increases. Some countries are introducing mandatory health insurance requirements or new charges for foreigners.


3. Local Attitude towards Expats – Be wary of resentment towards ex-pats as you may be blamed by locals as the reason house prices are high. Conversely, some countries have programmes to encourage foreigners to retire. It is worth investigating.


4. Grandchildren and Homesickness - Retiring to a new country, where you don’t have a circle of friends can be a difficult transition and can lead to feelings of isolation. 


5. Local Knowledge - If you have decided on retiring abroad, consider renting before you buy a house. This will give you the time and means to explore the local neighbourhood before committing.


To read more tips for Expats take a look at our dedicated blog, you can find it here.
